{"questionId":"27703","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A particle moves in a straight line. Its displacement, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>s</mi></math> metres, from a fixed point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>P</mtext></math> at&nbsp;time <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> seconds is given by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>s</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></msup></math>, for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn></math>, as shown in the following graph.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/0f93d8dfeb35b4287bd371d2a42be592699f154c.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The acceleration of the particle is zero when <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>b</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>c</mi></math>, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>c</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math> and the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>recognizing that acceleration is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mfenced><mi>t</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>v</mi><mo>'</mo><mfenced><mi>t</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mfenced><mi>t</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>s</mi><mo>'</mo><mo>'</mo><mfenced><mi>t</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>attempting to find max/min on graph of velocity OR finding zeros on graph of acceleration&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>23140</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>68959</mn><mo>…</mo></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>23</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>69</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[4 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"27703","referenceCode":"22N.2.SL.TZ0.7d","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Find the value of b and the value of c.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"d","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.9—Kinematics problems","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.4—Key features of graphs, intersections using technology"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}